    "short_descriptor": "Late-19th-century ornamental style, originally British, broadly American 1860-1900.",
    "background_prose": "Victorian architecture covers a family of late-19th-century styles named for Queen Victoria's reign (1837-1901). In American residential terms, 'Victorian' usually means Queen Anne Revival (1880-1910) or Stick Style: ornate decorative trim, asymmetric facades with bay windows or corner turrets, decorative scallop and fishscale shingles in the gable ends, wraparound porches with turned spindles, and multi-color 'Painted Lady' palettes. The Bay Area Painted Ladies of San Francisco are the canonical example.",
    "facade_features": [
      "Ornate decorative gingerbread trim",
      "Asymmetric facade, often with a rounded bay or corner turret",
      "Decorative scallop and fishscale shingles in gables",
      "Wraparound porch with turned spindle railings",
      "Multi-color 'Painted Lady' palette"
    ],
