  "consider": {
    "kicker": "Things to consider · before you commit",
    "title_html": "Three things <em>most</em> homeowners forget.",
    "items": [
      {
        "number": "01.",
        "heading": "Victorian rewards specificity.",
        "body": "Victorian rewards specificity. The decorative gingerbread trim is the diagnostic feature -- without it, the same complex roof line and asymmetric facade reads as cluttered rather than 'Painted Lady.' Specify trim color separately from siding color and budget extra paint complexity. A three- or four-color palette is architecturally correct."
      },
      {
        "number": "02.",
        "heading": "Brown reads as architecturally correct on warm-tone elevations.",
        "body": "Brown asphalt sits naturally with red brick, cream stucco, natural stone, and bronze hardware -- the warm-tone material families that traditional and revival styles depend on. On stark cool palettes (white-and-black, white-and-charcoal modern farmhouse) brown can read as dated; on warm palettes it reads as deliberate."
      },
      {
        "number": "03.",
        "heading": "Install quality matters more than SKU.",
        "body": "All seven recommended SKUs hit Class A fire and 110-150 mph wind ratings. The bigger variable on a victorian elevation is install quality: ridge-line straightness, valley flashing, starter strip alignment. Insist on a Master Elite or equivalent certified contractor and a written workmanship warranty separate from the manufacturer's material warranty."
      }
    ]
  },
